export const MUSCLE_DESCRIPTIONS = {
  Chest: 'The chest brings the upper arm across and in front of the torso. It drives every pressing pattern — flat, incline, and decline — along with fly and dip work, and shapes the front of the upper body.',
  Abductors: 'The hip abductors move the thigh away from the midline and keep the pelvis level when weight shifts onto one leg. They matter for squat tracking, single-leg stability, and controlling knee position under load.',
  Abs: 'The abdominal wall flexes the spine and helps brace the rib cage over the pelvis. In training it transfers force between upper and lower body while limiting unwanted trunk movement.',
  Adductors: 'The adductors draw the thigh toward the midline and assist hip extension from deep positions. They contribute heavily to squat depth, stance control, and lateral stability.',
  Biceps: 'The biceps flex the elbow and help rotate the forearm palm-up. They also assist pulling movements by keeping the elbow path strong as the back produces most of the larger force.',
  Calves: 'The calves plantarflex the ankle, pushing the forefoot down against the ground or machine. They support jumping, running, loaded carries, and stable lower-body positions.',
  Core: 'The core resists motion through the trunk rather than only creating it. It keeps the spine and pelvis organized while force moves through the arms, legs, and loaded implements.',
  Forearms: 'The forearms control wrist position, finger flexion, and grip. Strong forearms keep the hand connected to the implement so pulling, curling, and carrying work can be expressed.',
  'Front Delts': 'The front delts raise the upper arm forward and assist pressing. They are most active when the arm travels in front of the torso, especially in overhead and incline angles.',
  Glutes: 'The glutes extend, abduct, and externally rotate the hip. They drive hip lockout, help control the pelvis, and keep the femur tracking well during squats, hinges, and lunges.',
  Hamstrings: 'The hamstrings extend the hip and flex the knee. They load heavily in hinges, help decelerate the leg, and support posterior-chain strength around the hip and knee.',
  'Hip Flexors': 'The hip flexors lift the thigh toward the torso and help control pelvic position. They show up in leg raises, sprinting mechanics, and exercises where the trunk and thigh close together.',
  Lats: 'The lats pull the upper arm down and back toward the torso. They shape vertical pulls, rows, pullovers, and the shoulder stability needed for heavy pressing and deadlifting.',
  'Lower Back': 'The lower back extensors hold and extend the spine against load. In hinges and carries they work mostly as stabilizers, keeping the trunk rigid while the hips produce force.',
  'Lower Chest': 'The lower chest fibers pull the upper arm downward and across the torso. Decline presses, dips, and low-to-high arm paths bias this region more than flat or incline pressing.',
  'Mid Chest': 'The mid chest brings the upper arm across the body in a horizontal path. Flat presses, push-ups, and fly patterns load this region through shoulder horizontal adduction.',
  Neck: 'The neck muscles move and stabilize the head under changing body positions. Direct neck work trains controlled flexion, extension, and lateral resistance rather than large ranges under speed.',
  Obliques: 'The obliques rotate, side-bend, and brace the trunk. They are central to anti-rotation work, carries, twisting patterns, and keeping the rib cage stacked under asymmetrical load.',
  Quads: 'The quads extend the knee and help control knee bend under load. They dominate squats, leg presses, lunges, and extensions, especially when the knee travels forward over the foot.',
  'Rear Delts': 'The rear delts move the upper arm backward and outward. They support rows, face pulls, reverse fly work, and shoulder balance for athletes who press often.',
  Shoulders: 'The shoulder complex moves the upper arm through pressing, raising, and stabilizing patterns. Compound shoulder work usually blends delts, rotator cuff control, and upper-back positioning.',
  'Side Delts': 'The side delts raise the upper arm away from the body. They are the main target in lateral raise patterns and help build shoulder width through controlled abduction.',
  Tibialis: 'The tibialis anterior pulls the toes upward toward the shin. It supports ankle control, deceleration, and balance around the lower leg opposite the calves.',
  Traps: 'The traps elevate, retract, rotate, and stabilize the shoulder blades. They contribute to shrugs, carries, pulls from the floor, and overhead positions where the scapula must move well.',
  Triceps: 'The triceps extend the elbow and assist pressing. They finish lockout in presses, dips, and pushdowns while helping keep the elbow stable under load.',
  'Upper Back': 'The upper back retracts and stabilizes the shoulder blades while the arms pull. It gives rows their base, supports posture under a bar, and keeps pressing mechanics organized.',
  'Upper Chest': 'The upper chest flexes and adducts the shoulder on an upward angle. Incline presses, high cable flys, and landmine paths bias these fibers more than flat pressing.',
}

